Key Findings

  • NIG (Normal Inverse Gaussian) wins at every horizon — consistently lowest AIC
  • Laplace body is well-calibrated: GenNormal β ≈ 0.99 at 300–900s
  • Tails are heavier than Laplace — excess kurtosis 4.6–5.8 vs Laplace's 3.0
  • Short horizons (<30s) are dramatically non-Laplace (β=0.2–0.9)
  • Mild negative skew at longer horizons (−0.15 to −0.45)
  • Distribution choice matters most when time-to-expiry < 60s

Implications for FV Models

  • Current Laplace assumption is reasonable for body pricing (±2σ)
  • Deep OTM outcomes are underpriced — Laplace underweights tails beyond 3σ
  • NIG or Student-t (ν≈3) would improve tail accuracy for settlement pricing
  • Time-to-expiry matters: distribution choice is most impactful when TTE < 60s
